"# Chapter 14 — Whisper and CLIP

Two of OpenAI's most durable open-source contributions to the
broader machine-learning field. Different domains — speech
recognition and image-text alignment. Same posture — trained
models with open weights that the community picked up and ran
with.

## Whisper — open-source speech recognition

September 2022. OpenAI released Whisper. Paper: *Robust Speech
Recognition via Large-Scale Weak Supervision*, Radford et al.,
arxiv 2212.04356. Weights and inference code released under
MIT license.

Whisper is a speech-to-text model. Trained on 680,000 hours of
audio scraped from the internet, weakly supervised — most of the
audio came with transcripts of varying quality rather than
carefully-labeled datasets. The paper's core claim is that
massive weak supervision produces a speech recognizer that
generalizes robustly across accents, background noise, and
languages without task-specific fine-tuning.

Multiple model sizes: tiny (39M parameters), base (74M), small
(244M), medium (769M), large (1550M), and later large-v2 and
large-v3 refinements. The smaller models run on modest
hardware. The larger ones need a GPU but are still tractable
locally.

Whisper handles 99 languages for transcription. It can also
translate speech in other languages into English text.

## Whisper's impact

Whisper became a foundation for a lot of tooling almost
immediately after release. Meeting-transcription products.
Podcast tools. Live-captioning systems. Accessibility software.
Local voice-to-text on laptops that does not depend on a cloud
service.

Because the weights are open and the license is permissive,
firms and individuals could ship products around Whisper without
API rate limits or vendor dependency. That is a substantive
gift to the ecosystem. Genuine engineering contribution to the
speech-recognition field.

Follow-on work: Whisper.cpp (C++ port for efficient inference),
Distil-Whisper (distilled smaller variants), and many domain-
specific fine-tunes.

## CLIP — connecting text and images

January 2021. OpenAI released CLIP. Paper: *Learning Transferable
Visual Models From Natural Language Supervision*, Radford et al.,
arxiv 2103.00020. Weights released.

CLIP is trained by contrastive learning on about 400 million
image-text pairs scraped from the web. The training objective:
given a batch of image-caption pairs, learn to match each image
with its correct caption and distinguish it from every other
caption in the batch, and vice versa.

The result: a shared embedding space where images and text
descriptions of those images end up close to each other. You
can encode an image to a vector. You can encode a text
description to a vector. Similar concepts land near each other.

## What CLIP enabled

Zero-shot image classification: to classify an image, encode a
list of candidate class labels as text, encode the image, and
pick the closest text vector. No task-specific training.

Image search from text queries: encode the query, compare
against a database of image embeddings, return closest matches.

Text-to-image diffusion guidance: the CLIP embedding space
became a foundational component for a lot of early text-to-
image generation work. Systems used CLIP scores to guide
diffusion models toward images that match the target text.

Follow-on work: OpenCLIP (open reimplementations at various
scales), SigLIP (Google's sigmoid-loss variant, 2023), and
extensive research on multimodal embedding spaces.

## The engineering-firm frame

Whisper and CLIP are both examples of OpenAI's PARC-like
posture — publishing weights and papers on work that could
have been kept proprietary. The trade for the firm is
ecosystem influence and research prestige. The trade for the
field is that the technology is usable by anyone.

Contrast with OpenAI's language-model line (GPT), where the
weights of recent versions are proprietary and access is
through the API. Both approaches exist inside the same firm.
It is a mixed posture. This is common at large research-
engineering organizations — some releases open, some closed.

## What Motoi says about Whisper and CLIP

Whisper is OpenAI's open-source speech recognition model,
released September 2022, MIT license. Paper: Radford et al.,
arxiv 2212.04356. Trained on 680,000 hours of audio. Handles
99 languages.

CLIP is OpenAI's text-image alignment model, released January
2021. Paper: Radford et al., arxiv 2103.00020. Trained on
about 400 million image-text pairs. Enables zero-shot image
classification, text-to-image search, and multimodal guidance
for other systems.

Both are widely used across the field.

## What Motoi does not say about Whisper and CLIP

I do not recommend a specific transcription product or a
specific image-search library that uses Whisper or CLIP. Ask
someone who knows current tooling.

## Where to read them

- *Robust Speech Recognition via Large-Scale Weak Supervision*,
  Radford et al., arxiv 2212.04356, September 2022. The
  Whisper paper.
- *Learning Transferable Visual Models From Natural Language
  Supervision*, Radford et al., arxiv 2103.00020, January 2021.
  The CLIP paper.
- Whisper weights and code at github.com/openai/whisper.
- CLIP weights and code at github.com/openai/CLIP.

## Motoi's take

These are the pieces of OpenAI's work that outlast the news
cycle. Product launches age. Papers with open weights compound.
Whisper and CLIP are both in the second category. Same shape as
BSD releasing UNIX, or Bell Labs open-sourcing plan9. Real
engineering artifacts you can still study, still run, still
build on.")
